
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `kmod` baraye modiriyat module-haye hasteye Linux (Linux kernel modules) estefade mishavad. Module-ha code-haye ezafi hastand ke mitavanand be h هسته ezafe shavand ta functionality ra behtar konand. ba `kmod` mitavan module-ha ra list kard, load kard, ya remove kard.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `kmod list`  --> 📜 List kardane hameye module-haye load shode.
    🔹 `kmod insert <module_name>` --> ➕ Load kardane yek module be هسته.
    🔹 `kmod remove <module_name>` --> ➖ Remove kardane yek module az هسته.
    🔹 `kmod info <module_name>` --> ℹ️ Namayeshe etela'at dar morede yek module.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ kmod list

    🔹 Namayeshe hameye module-haye فعّal.

    $ kmod insert example_module

    🔹 Load kardane module به name 'example_module'.

    $ kmod remove example_module

    🔹 Remove kardane module 'example_module' az هسته.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ kmod list | grep usb

    🔹 Peida kardane module-haye مرتبط با usb dar list module-haye فعّal. In komak mikonad ta bebinim aya module usb correctly load shode ast ya na.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `kmod` command is used for managing Linux kernel modules. Modules are pieces of code that can be loaded into the kernel to extend its functionality. With `kmod`, you can list, insert (load), or remove modules from the kernel.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `kmod list`  --> 📜 List all currently loaded kernel modules.
    🔹 `kmod insert <module_name>` --> ➕ Load a kernel module.
    🔹 `kmod remove <module_name>` --> ➖ Remove a kernel module.
    🔹 `kmod info <module_name>` --> ℹ️ Show information about a specific module.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ kmod list

    🔹 Show all currently active modules.

    $ kmod insert example_module

    🔹 Load the module named 'example_module'.

    $ kmod remove example_module

    🔹 Remove the module 'example_module' from the kernel.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ kmod list | grep usb

    🔹 Find modules related to USB from the list of active modules. This helps to verify if the USB module is loaded correctly.
